  "prompt": "What is the formula to calculate a synchronous speed of a motor?",
  "response": "The formula to calculate the synchronous speed of an AC motor is:\n\nNs = (120 * f) / P\n\nWhere:\nNs = Synchronous speed (in revolutions per minute, RPM)\nf = Frequency of the power supply (in Hertz, Hz)\nP = Number of poles in the motor\n\nKey points:\n- Typically used for three-phase AC motors\n- Standard power supply frequency is 50 Hz or 60 Hz\n- More poles result in lower synchronous speed\n- This formula assumes an ideal, unloaded motor condition\n\nExample:\nFor a 4-pole motor at 60 Hz:\nNs = (120 * 60) / 4 = 1,800 RPM",
